owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Carbon Black', 'Acetylene Carbon Black', 'High-Purity Carbon Black', 'Conductive Carbon Additive', 'AB']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Acetylene Black is a high-purity form of carbon black, consisting of fine particles of elemental carbon. It is commonly used as a conductive additive in lithium-ion batteries and fuel cells, due to its high surface area, electrical conductivity, and chemical stability.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['CB', 'Conductive Carbon Black', 'Amorphous Carbon Black', 'Carbon Black Additive', 'High Surface Area Carbon']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Carbon black is a form of amorphous carbon, consisting of fine particles produced by the incomplete combustion of hydrocarbons. It is used as a conductive additive in lithium-ion batteries, fuel cells, and supercapacitors, due to its high surface area, electrical conductivity, and electrochemical stability.

A material is any substance that has a defined chemical composition and physical properties. In the context of hydrogen technologies, materials are used in various applications such as fuel cells, electrolyzers, and hydrogen storage. Examples of materials used in these applications include metals, ceramics, polymers, and composites.

Acid is a chemical compound that donates hydrogen ions (H+) to a solution, lowering its pH and increasing its acidity. Acids are commonly used in hydrogen technologies as electrolytes in fuel cells and batteries to facilitate ion transport and electrochemical reactions.

A Chemical Substance is any material with a definite chemical composition. It can be a pure substance or a mixture of substances. In hydrogen technologies, chemical substances are used as reactants, catalysts, and electrolytes in various electrochemical processes, such as fuel cells, electrolyzers, and batteries.

A chemical entity is any substance or compound that has a distinct molecular composition and is capable of undergoing a chemical reaction. It can be a pure substance or a mixture of substances, and can be either organic or inorganic.

A Molecular Entity is an electrically neutral group of two or more atoms held together by chemical bonds. It can be a molecule, an ion, or a radical. Molecular entities are the building blocks of all chemical substances and play a crucial role in materials science and hydrogen technologies.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Acidic Solution Electrolyte', 'Low-pH Electrolyte', 'Acidic Fuel Cell Electrolyte', 'Acidic Battery Electrolyte']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: An acidic electrolyte is an electrolyte solution with a pH less than 7, commonly used in electrochemical devices such as batteries and fuel cells. It provides a source of ions for the electrochemical reactions to occur and facilitates the movement of ions between the electrodes.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Water-Based Electrolyte', 'Hydrophilic Electrolyte', 'Aqueous Solution', 'Water-Based Ionic Liquid', 'Water-Based Salt Solution']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: An Aqueous Electrolyte is an electrolyte solution composed of water and dissolved salts or acids. It is commonly used in electrochemical devices such as batteries, fuel cells, and supercapacitors, due to its high ionic conductivity and low cost.

An electrolyte solution is a liquid or gel containing ions that conducts electricity and is used in batteries, fuel cells, and other electrochemical devices. It facilitates the movement of ions between the electrodes, allowing the electrochemical reactions to occur.

An electrolyte solution is a liquid or gel that contains ions and can conduct electricity. It is used in batteries, fuel cells, and other electrochemical devices to facilitate the movement of ions between the electrodes and maintain charge balance.

Actinium is a radioactive chemical element with the symbol Ac and atomic number 89. It is a silvery-white, highly radioactive metal that is found in uranium ores. Actinium has potential applications in nuclear batteries, cancer treatment, and as a neutron source.

An atom is the basic unit of matter, consisting of a nucleus (protons and neutrons) and electrons that orbit the nucleus. Atoms are the building blocks of all chemical elements and are characterized by their atomic number, mass number, and electron configuration.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Electrode Active Material', 'Battery Active Material', 'Active Cathode Material', 'Active Anode Material']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: An active material is a substance that undergoes electrochemical reactions during charge and discharge cycles in a battery or electrochemical cell. It is responsible for storing and releasing electrical energy in the device. Examples of active materials include lithium cobalt oxide, graphite, and sulfur.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Electroactive Material', 'Electrode Material', 'Electrolyte Material', 'Redox Material', 'Electrochemically Active Material']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: An electrochemical material is a substance that can undergo electrochemical reactions, such as oxidation and reduction, in an electrochemical cell. These materials are used in batteries, fuel cells, and other electrochemical devices to store and convert energy.

A functional material is a material that has specific properties or functions that make it useful for a particular application. These materials are designed to have specific physical, chemical, or biological properties that can be tailored to meet the needs of a particular application. Examples of functional materials include catalysts, semiconductors, superconductors, and biomaterials.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Aerosol Synthesis', 'Aerosol-based Method', 'Aerosol Deposition', 'Aerosol Jet Printing', 'Aerosol Coating']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: An aerosol is a suspension of fine solid or liquid particles in a gas. In hydrogen technologies, aerosols can be used for the synthesis of nanoparticles, catalysts, and fuel cell components. Aerosol-based methods offer advantages such as high surface area, uniform particle size distribution, and precise control over particle morphology.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Colloidal Suspension', 'Colloidal System', 'Dispersed Phase System', 'Colloidal Dispersion', 'Colloidal Solution']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A colloid is a mixture in which one substance is dispersed evenly throughout another substance. The dispersed substance is usually in the form of particles, which are larger than individual molecules but small enough to remain suspended in the mixture. Colloids have important applications in materials science, including in the synthesis of nanoparticles and in the design of advanced materials.

A gas mixture is a combination of two or more gases in a container, where the gases are not chemically combined. Gas mixtures are commonly used in hydrogen technologies, such as fuel cells, for various applications, including fuel storage, gas purification, and gas separation.

A dispersion is a mixture of two or more substances that do not dissolve in each other. The dispersed phase is made up of small particles that are suspended in the continuous phase. In materials science, dispersions are used to create composite materials with unique properties.

A Phase Heterogeneous Mixture is a mixture of two or more substances that are not uniformly distributed and can be distinguished by their physical properties, such as color, density, or refractive index. Examples include suspensions, emulsions, and foams.

A suspension is a type of heterogeneous mixture in which solid particles are dispersed in a liquid medium. The solid particles are usually insoluble in the liquid and will settle over time if left undisturbed. Suspensions are commonly used in various industrial applications, such as in the production of paints, pigments, and pharmaceuticals.

A mixture is a combination of two or more substances that are not chemically bonded and can be separated by physical means. Mixtures can be homogeneous or heterogeneous and can exist in any state of matter.

Air is a mixture of gases, primarily nitrogen (78%) and oxygen (21%), with trace amounts of other gases such as argon, carbon dioxide, and neon. It is a common oxidant used in fuel cells and other electrochemical devices.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Homogeneous Solid Mixture', 'Single-Phase Solid Solution', 'Solid-State Alloy', 'Crystallographic Solid Solution']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A solid solution is a solid-state mixture of two or more substances that combine to form a single crystalline phase. In solid solutions, the atoms of the different components are randomly distributed throughout the crystal lattice, resulting in a homogeneous material with unique properties.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Solid Blend', 'Solid Composite', 'Solid Solution', 'Solid Suspension', 'Solid Heterogeneous Mixture']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A Solid Mixture is a combination of two or more solid materials that are physically mixed together, but not chemically bonded. Solid mixtures can be homogeneous or heterogeneous and are commonly used in materials science for tailoring properties such as strength, conductivity, and thermal stability.

An electrolyte is a substance that produces ions when dissolved in a solvent, typically a liquid. Electrolytes are used in electrochemical cells to facilitate the movement of ions between the anode and cathode, allowing for the flow of electrical current.

Alcohol is a class of organic compounds that contain a hydroxyl (-OH) functional group. It is commonly used as a solvent, fuel, and feedstock in chemical synthesis. In hydrogen technologies, alcohols such as methanol and ethanol are used as fuel in fuel cells.

An amphiphilic solvent is a solvent that contains both hydrophilic (water-loving) and hydrophobic (water-fearing) regions in its molecular structure. These solvents are commonly used in materials science and electrochemistry as they can dissolve both polar and nonpolar substances. Examples of amphiphilic solvents include water-miscible organic solvents like ethanol and methanol.

A solvent is a substance that dissolves a solute to form a solution. In hydrogen technologies, solvents are used in various processes such as electrolyte preparation, catalyst synthesis, and fuel cell fabrication. Common solvents include water, alcohols, and organic solvents such as dimethyl sulfoxide (DMSO) and N-methyl-2-pyrrolidone (NMP).

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Alicyclic Organic Molecules', 'Heterocyclic Organic Molecules', 'Cyclic Organic Compounds', 'Ring-Containing Organic Molecules', 'Organic Heterocycles']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Alicyclic and Heterocyclic Organic Molecules are organic compounds that contain cyclic structures, such as rings, and may also contain heteroatoms, such as nitrogen, oxygen, or sulfur. These molecules have diverse applications in materials science, including as solvents, monomers, and ligands for catalysis and coordination chemistry.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Heterocyclic Compounds', 'Heterocycles', 'Organic Heterocyclic Molecules', 'Heteroaromatic Compounds', 'Heteroatom-Containing Organic Molecules']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Heterocyclic organic molecules are organic compounds that contain at least one heteroatom (an atom other than carbon) in their ring structure. They have diverse applications in materials science, including as dyes, pharmaceuticals, and organic semiconductors.

Aromatic heterocyclic organic molecules are organic compounds that contain a ring structure made up of carbon atoms and at least one heteroatom (such as nitrogen, oxygen, or sulfur) in the ring. These molecules have unique electronic properties that make them useful in a variety of applications, including as dyes, pharmaceuticals, and organic semiconductors.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Cyclic Organic Compounds', 'Cyclic Organic Chemicals', 'Cyclic Molecules', 'Ring-Structured Organic Molecules', 'Heterocyclic Molecules']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Cyclic organic molecules are organic compounds that contain one or more closed rings of atoms in their structure. They have a wide range of applications in materials science, including as building blocks for polymers, pharmaceuticals, and agrochemicals.

Homocyclic Organic Molecules are organic compounds that contain only carbon atoms in their rings. These molecules are also known as carbocyclic compounds and are classified based on the number of carbon atoms in their rings. They have various applications in organic synthesis, pharmaceuticals, and materials science.

Alicyclic homocyclic organic molecules are cyclic organic compounds that contain only carbon atoms in the ring structure. They are characterized by having a closed ring of atoms with no double or triple bonds and are commonly used as solvents, monomers, and intermediates in organic synthesis.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Aromatic-Cyclic Organic Compounds', 'Aromatic-Aliphatic Organic Molecules', 'Aromatic-Cyclic Hydrocarbons', 'Alicyclic-Aromatic Compounds', 'Aromatic-Cyclic Organic Polymers']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Aromatic Alicyclic Organic Molecules are organic compounds that contain both aromatic and alicyclic (non-aromatic cyclic) structural elements. These molecules have unique properties, such as high thermal stability, rigidity, and resistance to oxidation, making them useful in various applications, including as solvents, monomers, and pharmaceuticals.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Alkaline Fuel Cell Electrolyte', 'KOH Electrolyte', 'NaOH Electrolyte', 'Basic Electrolyte']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: An Alkaline Electrolyte is a type of electrolyte used in alkaline fuel cells, consisting of a solution of potassium hydroxide (KOH) or sodium hydroxide (NaOH) in water. Alkaline electrolytes offer high ionic conductivity and are less prone to carbonation than acidic electrolytes.

Alkanes are a family of organic compounds consisting of carbon and hydrogen atoms, with only single covalent bonds between the atoms. They are commonly used as fuels and solvents in hydrogen technologies, and can be converted into hydrogen gas through steam reforming or other processes.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Acyclic Organic Molecules', 'Aliphatic Organic Molecules', 'Linear Organic Molecules', 'Branched Organic Molecules', 'Non-Cyclic Organic Molecules']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Open-chain organic molecules, also known as acyclic or aliphatic molecules, are organic compounds that do not contain a cyclic structure. They are characterized by a linear or branched chain of carbon atoms, and can include functional groups such as alkanes, alkenes, and alkynes. Open-chain organic molecules have a wide range of applications in organic chemistry, materials science, and biochemistry.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Cyclic Organic Compound', 'Ringed Organic Molecule', 'Cyclic Organic Chemistry', 'Cyclic Carbon Compound', 'Cyclic Hydrocarbon']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A cyclic organic molecule is a type of organic molecule that contains a closed ring of atoms in its structure. These molecules have a wide range of applications in materials science, including as building blocks for polymers, pharmaceuticals, and agrochemicals.

Alkenes are unsaturated hydrocarbons that contain at least one carbon-carbon double bond. They are important in hydrogen technologies as they can be used as feedstocks for the production of hydrogen gas through steam methane reforming or partial oxidation.
Alkynes are unsaturated hydrocarbons that contain a carbon-carbon triple bond. They are used in organic synthesis, as starting materials for the production of polymers, and as fuels.

Aluminum is a lightweight, corrosion-resistant metal with good electrical conductivity. It is commonly used in hydrogen technologies as a component of fuel cell bipolar plates, hydrogen storage tanks, and electrolysis electrodes.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Am', 'Actinide Metal', 'Radioactive Element', 'Smoke Detector Material', 'Nuclear Battery Material']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Americium is a radioactive, silvery-white metal that is part of the actinide series. It is primarily used in nuclear research and as a source of ionizing radiation for industrial gauges and smoke detectors. Americium has potential applications in nuclear batteries and spacecraft power systems.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Negative Ion', 'Anionic Species', 'Anionic Particle', 'Anode Ion', 'Negatively Charged Species']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: An anion is a negatively charged ion that migrates to the anode (positive electrode) in an electrolytic cell. It is an atom or molecule that has gained one or more electrons, resulting in a net negative charge.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Charged Particle', 'Electrically Charged Atom', 'Electrically Charged Molecule', 'Cation or Anion', 'Ionized Particle']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: An ion is an atom or molecule that has an unequal number of protons and electrons, resulting in a net electrical charge. Ions can be positively charged (called cations) or negatively charged (called anions) and play important roles in electrochemical reactions.

An Anisotropic Material is a material that exhibits different properties in different directions. It has physical or mechanical properties that vary with the direction of measurement. Anisotropic materials are commonly used in fuel cell and battery components, such as electrodes and membranes, to optimize their performance in specific directions.

Matter is anything that has mass and takes up space. It can exist in three states: solid, liquid, or gas. In materials science, matter is studied to understand its properties and behavior, and to develop new materials with desired properties.

An anolyte is an electrolyte solution that is located at the anode of an electrochemical cell. It is responsible for providing ions to the anode and facilitating the electrochemical reactions that occur at the anode during cell operation.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Liquid Electrolytic Solution', 'Conductive Liquid', 'Electrolyte Liquid', 'Liquid Ionic Conductor', 'Liquid Salt']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A Liquid Electrolyte is a conductive solution used in batteries and fuel cells to facilitate the movement of ions between the electrodes. It is typically composed of a solvent and a dissolved salt or other ionic compound, and can be either aqueous or non-aqueous.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Homogeneous Liquid Mixture', 'Liquid Solvent Mixture', 'Liquid Phase Solution', 'Liquid Homogeneous Mixture']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A liquid solution is a homogeneous mixture of two or more substances in which the molecules or atoms of the substances are evenly distributed. The solvent is the substance that dissolves the solute(s) to form the solution. Liquid solutions are commonly used in chemical reactions, separations, and as solvents for other substances.

Antimony is a chemical element with the symbol Sb and atomic number 51. It is a lustrous, gray metalloid that is commonly used as a flame retardant, alloyed with lead for batteries, and used in the production of semiconductors.

An aqueous electrolyte is a solution containing ions that conducts electricity and is composed of water as the solvent. It is commonly used in electrochemical devices such as batteries, fuel cells, and supercapacitors.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Water-based solution', 'Hydrophilic solution', 'Water solvent mixture', 'Aqua solution', 'Water solution']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: An aqueous solution is a solution in which the solvent is water. It is commonly used in electrochemistry as an electrolyte solution, where it facilitates the movement of ions between the electrodes. Aqueous solutions are also used in a wide range of chemical reactions and industrial processes.

An aqueous molecule is a molecule that is dissolved in water, forming an aqueous solution. These molecules can be organic or inorganic and are commonly used in chemical reactions and biological processes.

A dissolved molecule is a molecule that is uniformly dispersed in a solvent to form a homogeneous solution. The dissolved molecule can be a solute, which is the substance being dissolved, or a solvent, which is the substance doing the dissolving. Dissolved molecules play a critical role in many chemical and biological processes, including solubility, transport, and reaction kinetics.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Non-Water Soluble Molecule', 'Non-Aqueous Solvent', 'Non-Polar Solvent', 'Organic Solvent', 'Non-Aqueous Electrolyte']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A non-aqueous molecule is a molecule that is not soluble in water or does not contain water as a solvent. Non-aqueous solvents are commonly used in electrochemical applications, such as in lithium-ion batteries and supercapacitors, due to their high chemical stability and wide electrochemical window.

A Molecular Entity in State of Aggregation refers to a chemical species that is composed of two or more molecules held together by intermolecular forces. Examples include dimers, trimers, and other oligomers. These species can have unique properties and reactivity compared to their individual molecular components.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['PFSA Ionomer Membrane', 'Aquivion Membrane', 'Proton-Conducting Membrane', 'PEM Membrane', 'Fuel Cell Membrane']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Aquivion is a perfluorosulfonic acid (PFSA) ionomer membrane used in proton exchange membrane (PEM) fuel cells. It offers high proton conductivity, chemical stability, and mechanical durability, making it a popular choice for fuel cell applications.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Perfluorosulfonic Acid Ionomer', 'PFSA Ionomer', 'Proton-Conducting Ionomer', 'Aquivion Ionomer Membrane', 'Sulfonated Ionomer']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Ionomers are a class of materials that contain ionic groups, which can conduct ions. They are used in fuel cells and other electrochemical devices as membranes or coatings to facilitate ion transport. Aquivion is a type of ionomer that is based on perfluorosulfonic acid and is known for its high proton conductivity and chemical stability.

A polymer is a large molecule composed of repeating subunits called monomers. Polymers have a wide range of applications in hydrogen technologies, including as electrolyte membranes, ionomers, and electrode binders in fuel cells and batteries.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['D72-25BS', 'Aquivion Membrane', 'Perfluorosulfonic Acid Ionomer', 'PFSA Ionomer', 'Proton Exchange Membrane']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Aquivion D72-25BS is a perfluorosulfonic acid ionomer membrane used in proton exchange membrane fuel cells. It has a high proton conductivity, good chemical stability, and high mechanical strength, making it suitable for use in harsh environments.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['D79-25BS', 'Perfluorosulfonic Acid Ionomer', 'Proton Exchange Membrane', 'PEM', 'Fuel Cell Membrane']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Aquivion D79-25BS is a perfluorosulfonic acid ionomer membrane used in proton exchange membrane fuel cells. It has a high ion exchange capacity and good mechanical properties, making it suitable for use in high-temperature and low-humidity environments.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['D98-25BS', 'Perfluorosulfonic Acid Ionomer', 'High-Temperature PEM', 'Proton Exchange Membrane', 'PEM Fuel Cell Membrane']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Aquivion D98-25BS is a perfluorosulfonic acid ionomer membrane used in proton exchange membrane fuel cells. It has a high ion exchange capacity and excellent proton conductivity, making it suitable for use in high-temperature fuel cells.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Aquivion Proton Exchange Membrane', 'Aquivion SO3H', 'Aquivion PFSA', 'Perfluorosulfonic Acid Membrane', 'PFSA Ionomer']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Aquivion SO3H-Form is a perfluorosulfonic acid ionomer used as a proton exchange membrane in fuel cells. It has a high proton conductivity, good chemical stability, and high thermal stability, making it suitable for use in high-temperature fuel cells.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Aromatic Heterocyclic Amines', 'Aromatic Heterocyclic Amine Compounds', 'Aromatic Heterocyclic Organic Nitrogen Compounds', 'Aromatic Heterocyclic Organic Amine Derivatives']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Aromatic Heterocyclic Organic Amines Molecules are organic compounds that contain both an amine group and an aromatic heterocyclic ring in their structure. They are used in various applications such as pharmaceuticals, agrochemicals, and dyes. These molecules exhibit unique electronic and steric properties, making them useful in a wide range of chemical reactions.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['As', 'Metalloid As', 'Arsenic Element', 'Arsenic Compound', 'Arsenic Semiconductor Doping Agent']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Arsenic is a chemical element with the symbol As and atomic number 33. It is a metalloid commonly used in the semiconductor industry and as a doping agent in some electronic devices. Arsenic and its compounds are also used in wood preservatives, pesticides, and herbicides, but are highly toxic and carcinogenic.

Astatine is a rare and highly radioactive element with the symbol At and atomic number 85. It is a member of the halogen family and is the heaviest known halogen. Astatine has no stable isotopes and is typically produced by bombarding bismuth with alpha particles. It has potential applications in targeted alpha-particle therapy for cancer treatment.

Barium is a chemical element with the symbol Ba and atomic number 56. It is a soft, silvery-white metal that belongs to the alkaline earth metals. Barium has a variety of applications, including in the production of vacuum tubes, fluorescent lamps, and fireworks.

A base is a substance that can accept hydrogen ions (protons) or donate hydroxide ions in a chemical reaction. In electrochemistry, bases are used as electrolytes in alkaline batteries and fuel cells, where they facilitate the flow of ions between the electrodes.

Berkelium is a synthetic, radioactive element with the symbol Bk and atomic number 97. It is a member of the actinide series and is named after the city of Berkeley, California, where it was first synthesized. Berkelium has no commercial applications but is used in scientific research, particularly in the study of nuclear properties and as a target material for the synthesis of heavier elements.

Beryllium is a lightweight, strong, and brittle metal that is commonly used as a structural material in aerospace, defense, and nuclear industries. It is also used as a neutron reflector in nuclear reactors and in X-ray windows due to its low atomic number and high transparency to X-rays.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Pt/C Catalyst', 'Carbon-Supported Pt Catalyst', 'Platinum-Carbon Catalyst', 'Pt/CB Catalyst', 'Binary Pt/C Catalyst']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A Binary Carbon Supported Platinum Catalyst is a type of catalyst used in fuel cells, consisting of platinum nanoparticles supported on a carbon black substrate. It is used as a cathode catalyst in proton exchange membrane fuel cells, offering high activity, stability, and durability.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Pt Catalyst', 'Platinum-Based Catalyst', 'Platinum Group Metal Catalyst', 'Pt/C Catalyst', 'Carbon-Supported Pt Catalyst']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A Platinum Catalyst is a material that accelerates chemical reactions by providing an alternative pathway with lower activation energy. It is commonly used in fuel cells, electrolyzers, and other electrochemical devices to facilitate the conversion of reactants into products. Platinum is a popular catalyst material due to its high activity, stability, and resistance to corrosion.

A Single Metal Catalyst is a type of catalyst that consists of only one type of metal, such as platinum, palladium, or iridium. It is used in various chemical reactions, including hydrogenation, oxidation, and reduction, to increase the rate of the reaction and improve its efficiency.

A binary catalyst is a type of catalyst composed of two different elements or compounds. In hydrogen technologies, binary catalysts are commonly used in fuel cells to promote the electrochemical reactions that convert hydrogen and oxygen into water and electricity. Examples of binary catalysts include platinum-ruthenium, platinum-tin, and platinum-cobalt.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Electrochemical Catalyst', 'Catalytic Electrode', 'Electrode Catalyst', 'Electrochemical Reaction Catalyst', 'Electrolysis Catalyst']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: An electrocatalyst is a material that increases the rate of an electrochemical reaction by lowering the activation energy required for the reaction to occur. It is used in electrochemical devices such as fuel cells, batteries, and electrolyzers to facilitate the conversion of chemical energy into electrical energy and vice versa.

A catalyst is a substance that increases the rate of a chemical reaction without undergoing any permanent chemical change itself. In hydrogen technologies, catalysts are used to facilitate the electrochemical reactions that convert chemical energy into electrical energy in fuel cells and electrolyzers.

A Binary Material is a material composed of two different chemical elements or compounds. In the context of hydrogen technologies, binary materials are often used as catalysts or electrode materials in fuel cells and electrolyzers.

Bismuth is a chemical element with the symbol Bi and atomic number 83. It is a dense, silvery-white metal with a pinkish tint. Bismuth is commonly used in cosmetics, alloys, and pharmaceuticals. It is also used as a substitute for lead in some applications due to its low toxicity.

Bohrium is a synthetic chemical element with the symbol Bh and atomic number 107. It is a highly radioactive metal and belongs to the group of transuranium elements. It is named after Danish physicist Niels Bohr.

Boron is a chemical element with the symbol B and atomic number 5. It is a metalloid and is commonly used in the form of borates, which are used in the production of glass, ceramics, and detergents. Boron is also used as a dopant in semiconductors and as a neutron absorber in nuclear reactors.

Bromine is a halogen element with the symbol Br and atomic number 35. It is a reddish-brown liquid at room temperature and is the only nonmetallic element that is liquid under normal conditions. Bromine is used in the production of flame retardants, water purification, and pharmaceuticals.

Cadmium is a soft, bluish-white metal that is commonly used in batteries, pigments, and coatings. It is also used in nuclear reactors as a neutron absorber and in solar cells as a semiconductor material.

Calcium is a chemical element with the symbol Ca and atomic number 20. It is a soft, silvery-white metal that belongs to the alkaline earth metals. Calcium is an important element in the production of alloys, as a reducing agent in the extraction of other metals, and in the production of cement and mortar.
Californium is a radioactive, synthetic element with the symbol Cf and atomic number 98. It is a highly reactive and rare element, primarily used in scientific research and nuclear reactors.

Carbon is a chemical element with the symbol C and atomic number 6. It is a non-metallic element and the fourth most abundant element in the universe. Carbon has several allotropes, including diamond, graphite, and fullerenes, and is a key element in organic chemistry and materials science.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Pt/C Catalyst', 'Carbon-Supported Pt Catalyst', 'Platinum on Carbon Catalyst', 'Pt Nanoparticle-Carbon Catalyst', 'Carbon-Platinum Catalyst']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A Carbon-Supported Platinum Catalyst is a type of electrocatalyst used in fuel cells, consisting of platinum nanoparticles supported on a carbon substrate. It is used to facilitate the oxygen reduction reaction (ORR) at the cathode in fuel cells, improving their efficiency and performance.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Catalyst Suspension', 'Catalyst Coating Ink', 'Electrode Catalyst Ink', 'Catalyst Deposition Ink', 'Catalyst Coating Solution']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A Catalyst Ink is a suspension of catalyst particles in a solvent, used for the deposition of catalyst layers onto electrode surfaces in fuel cells and other electrochemical devices. The ink is typically composed of a catalyst, a solvent, and a binder, and is applied to the electrode surface using various deposition techniques such as spraying, painting, or screen printing.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Redox Flow Battery Catholyte', 'Cathode Electrolyte Solution', 'Cathode Half-Cell Electrolyte', 'Cathodic Solution', 'Cathode Active Material']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A catholyte is an electrolyte solution that is used in redox flow batteries as the cathode half-cell. It is typically composed of a metal salt dissolved in a solvent and is responsible for facilitating the electrochemical reactions that occur at the cathode during battery operation.

A cation is an ion with a positive charge, which is formed when an atom loses one or more electrons. In electrochemistry, cations are attracted to the cathode, where they can gain electrons and be reduced.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Inorganic Ceramic Material', 'Ceramic Material', 'Ceramic Solid', 'Non-Metallic Material', 'Inorganic Solid']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Ceramic is a non-metallic, inorganic solid material that is typically made from a combination of metallic and non-metallic elements. Ceramics are used in a wide range of applications, including fuel cells, batteries, and catalysis, due to their high-temperature stability, chemical resistance, and electrical insulation properties.

Cerium is a chemical element with the symbol Ce and atomic number 58. It is a soft, silvery, ductile metal that easily oxidizes in air. Cerium is widely used in catalytic converters, glass polishing, and as a component of mischmetal, a pyrophoric alloy used in lighter flints.

Cesium is a highly reactive alkali metal with atomic number 55. It is used in various applications such as atomic clocks, photoelectric cells, and catalysts. Cesium-based catalysts are used in organic synthesis reactions, and as a promoter for other catalysts.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Carbon Channel Black', 'CB', 'Porous Carbon Additive', 'Lithium-Ion Battery Additive']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Channel Black is a form of carbon black that is used as a conductive additive in lithium-ion batteries. It is a highly porous material with a large surface area, which enhances the electrical conductivity and mechanical strength of the battery electrodes.

A chemical compound is a substance composed of two or more elements chemically bonded together in a fixed ratio. Chemical compounds have unique physical and chemical properties that differ from their constituent elements.

A Chemical Reaction Product is a substance formed as a result of a chemical reaction. It can be a solid, liquid, or gas and can have different properties than the reactants. In hydrogen technologies, chemical reaction products can include water, oxygen, and carbon dioxide.

A chemical reaction reactant is a substance that participates in a chemical reaction and undergoes a chemical change. It is typically consumed during the reaction and is transformed into one or more products.

Chlorine is a highly reactive, yellow-green gas that belongs to the halogen group of elements. It is widely used in the chemical industry for the production of a variety of chemicals, including solvents, pesticides, and plastics. Chlorine is also used as a disinfectant in water treatment and swimming pools.

Chromium is a chemical element with the symbol Cr and atomic number 24. It is a hard, lustrous, steel-gray metal that is highly resistant to corrosion and tarnishing. Chromium is widely used in the production of stainless steel, as well as in the aerospace, automotive, and electronics industries.

A coating substrate is a material onto which a coating is applied. The substrate can be a metal, ceramic, or polymer and is chosen based on the desired properties of the coating and the application requirements.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Co', 'Transition Metal Cobalt', 'Cobalt-Based Alloys', 'Cobalt Cathode Material', 'Cobalt Compounds']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Cobalt is a transition metal with the symbol Co and atomic number 27. It is commonly used in the production of rechargeable batteries, particularly in the cathode material of lithium-ion batteries. Cobalt-based alloys are also used in the manufacture of gas turbines, jet engines, and other high-performance machinery.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Composite', 'Composite System', 'Composite Structure', 'Composite Material System', 'Composite Material Structure']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A composite material is a material composed of two or more distinct phases, each with different physical and chemical properties, that when combined produce a material with improved properties compared to the individual components. In hydrogen technologies, composite materials are used in various applications, such as fuel cell electrodes, hydrogen storage tanks, and catalyst supports.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Conducting Polymer-Platinum Nanoparticle Composite', 'Conducting Polymer-Platinum Catalyst', 'Conducting Polymer-Supported Pt Catalyst', 'Conducting Polymer-Platinum Hybrid Catalyst', 'Polymer-Platinum Nanocomposite']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A Conducting Polymer Supported Platinum Catalyst is a composite material consisting of a conducting polymer matrix and platinum nanoparticles. It is used as a catalyst in fuel cells and offers improved catalytic activity, stability, and durability compared to other catalysts.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Continuous Material', 'Continuum Mechanics', 'Continuous Field Model', 'Continuum Approximation', 'Continuum Hypothesis']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: In materials science, a continuum refers to a continuous substance or material that can be modeled as a continuous field, without considering the discrete nature of its molecular or atomic structure. Continuum mechanics is a branch of mechanics that deals with the behavior of materials modeled as continua.

Copernicium is a synthetic, highly radioactive element with the symbol Cn and atomic number 112. It is a member of the transactinide elements and is currently only produced in nuclear reactors. Its properties are not well known due to its short half-life and difficulty in producing it in large quantities.

A copolymer is a polymer made up of two or more different monomers. Copolymers can have unique properties compared to homopolymers, such as improved mechanical strength, thermal stability, and chemical resistance. They are used in a variety of applications, including coatings, adhesives, and plastics.

Copper is a ductile, malleable, and highly conductive metal that is widely used in electrical wiring, plumbing, and industrial applications. It is also used as a catalyst in various chemical reactions and as a component in alloys such as brass and bronze.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Crystalline Material', 'Ordered Solid', 'Crystal Lattice', 'Periodic Arrangement of Atoms']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A crystal is a solid material whose atoms are arranged in a highly ordered, repeating pattern extending in all three spatial dimensions. Crystals have a well-defined shape and exhibit unique physical and chemical properties, making them useful in a wide range of applications, including electronics, optics, and catalysis.

A crystal is a solid material whose atoms, molecules, or ions are arranged in a highly ordered, repeating pattern extending in all three spatial dimensions. Crystals exhibit unique physical and chemical properties, such as piezoelectricity, birefringence, and high thermal conductivity, making them useful in a wide range of applications, including electronics, optics, and energy storage.

State of Aggregation refers to the physical state of a material, such as solid, liquid, or gas. It is an important property that affects the behavior and properties of materials, including their reactivity, conductivity, and mechanical properties.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Cm', 'Actinide Element Cm', 'Synthetic Element Cm', 'Radioactive Element Cm']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Curium is a radioactive, synthetic element with the symbol Cm and atomic number 96. It is a member of the actinide series of elements and is named after Marie and Pierre Curie. Curium is used in the production of heavier actinides and as a source of alpha particles for nuclear physics research.
A molecule is a group of two or more atoms held together by chemical bonds. It is the smallest fundamental unit of a chemical compound that can take part in a chemical reaction.

Darmstadtium is a synthetic, highly radioactive element with the symbol Ds and atomic number 110. It is a member of the transactinide series and is named after the city of Darmstadt, Germany. Darmstadtium has no known biological role and is primarily used for scientific research purposes.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Ar', 'Noble Gas Argon', 'Protective Gas Argon', 'Inert Gas Argon']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Argon is a chemical element with the symbol Ar and atomic number 18. It is a TEST noble gas and is the third-most abundant gas in the Earth's atmosphere. Argon is used in various applications, including welding, lighting, and as a protective gas in the production of titanium and other reactive elements.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Flexible Ceramic Substrate', 'Flexible Metal Substrate', 'Thin-Film Substrate', 'Polymer-Based Substrate', 'Metal Foil Substrate']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A Decal Substrate is a thin, flexible substrate used in the fabrication of electronic devices, such as solar cells and flexible displays. It is made of a polymer or metal foil and is coated with a thin layer of ceramic or metal oxide to improve its mechanical and electrical properties.

PTFE (Polytetrafluoroethylene) substrate is a non-stick, low-friction material that is often used as a substrate for electrochemical applications. It is chemically inert, thermally stable, and has excellent electrical insulation properties.

Diazole is a heterocyclic organic compound containing two nitrogen atoms in a five-membered ring. It is used as a corrosion inhibitor and as a building block in the synthesis of pharmaceuticals, agrochemicals, and dyes.

Dubnium is a synthetic, radioactive element with the symbol Db and atomic number 105. It is highly unstable and has a very short half-life, making it difficult to study. Dubnium has no known biological role and is primarily used for scientific research purposes.

Dust is a fine powder consisting of tiny particles of various materials, such as soil, pollen, and minerals. It can be generated from various sources, including human activities, natural phenomena, and industrial processes. In hydrogen technologies, dust can cause contamination and reduce the efficiency of fuel cells and other electrochemical devices.

A Gas-Solid Suspension is a heterogeneous mixture of gas and solid particles, where the solid particles are suspended in the gas phase. It is commonly referred to as a 'dust cloud' and can be found in various industrial processes, such as powder handling and combustion.

Dysprosium is a rare earth element with the symbol Dy and atomic number 66. It is a silvery-white metal that is relatively stable in air and water. Dysprosium is used in the production of high-strength magnets, nuclear reactors, and lighting applications.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Carbon-Supported Platinum Catalyst EA30E', 'Platinum/C Carbon Catalyst EA30E', 'EA30E Catalyst Ink', 'High-Performance Pt/C Catalyst EA30E']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: EA30E is a high-performance, carbon-supported platinum catalyst used in proton exchange membrane fuel cells. It has a high platinum loading and offers improved activity and durability compared to other platinum-based catalysts.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['GFBC-supported Pt Catalyst', 'Graphitized Carbon Black-supported Pt Catalyst', 'Graphite Furnace Black Carbon-supported Pt Catalyst', 'GFBC-Pt Catalyst', 'Graphite Carbon Black-supported Pt Catalyst']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Graphitized Furnace Black Carbon Supported Platinum Catalyst is a composite material used as an electrocatalyst in fuel cells. It consists of a graphitized furnace black carbon substrate and platinum nanoparticles deposited on its surface. This catalyst offers high electrochemical activity, stability, and durability in fuel cell applications.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['High-Temperature-Resistant EA30E Catalyst', 'EA30E Catalyst for High-Temperature Applications', 'Graphitized Carbon-Supported Pt Catalyst', 'EA30E-HT Platinum Catalyst', 'HT-Resistant Pt/C Catalyst']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: EA30E-HT is a high-temperature-resistant, graphitized furnace black carbon-supported platinum catalyst. It is used in proton exchange membrane fuel cells and offers improved durability and stability at high temperatures compared to other platinum catalysts.

ETFE (Ethylene Tetrafluoroethylene) is a fluoropolymer material with high chemical resistance, thermal stability, and electrical insulation properties. It is commonly used as a coating or film in fuel cells, batteries, and other electrochemical devices due to its excellent barrier properties and durability.

PTFE (Polytetrafluoroethylene) is a synthetic fluoropolymer of tetrafluoroethylene. It is a non-reactive, thermoplastic polymer with excellent chemical resistance, high temperature tolerance, and low friction coefficient. PTFE is widely used in various applications, including as a coating material, insulator, and sealant.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Es', 'Radioactive Element Es', 'Actinide Series Element Es', 'Synthetic Element Es']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Einsteinium is a synthetic, radioactive element with the symbol Es and atomic number 99. It is a member of the actinide series and is named after physicist Albert Einstein. Einsteinium is primarily used for scientific research purposes.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Intercalation Electrode Material', 'Electrochemical Intercalation Compound', 'Intercalation Cathode Material', 'Intercalation Anode Material', 'Intercalation Battery Material']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: An Electrochemical Intercalation Material is a material that can undergo intercalation reactions with ions in an electrochemical cell. These materials are used as electrodes in batteries and supercapacitors, and can store and release ions during charge and discharge cycles. Examples include graphite, metal oxides, and transition metal dichalcogenides.

An electrochemical charge carrier ion is an ion that carries an electric charge in an electrochemical reaction. It can be either positively charged (cation) or negatively charged (anion) and is involved in the transfer of charge between electrodes in a battery or fuel cell.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Electrochemical Conversion Substance', 'Electroactive Material', 'Electrochemical Energy Conversion Material', 'Electrochemical Energy Storage Material']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: An electrochemical conversion material is a substance that can undergo a reversible electrochemical reaction, converting chemical energy into electrical energy or vice versa. These materials are used in batteries, fuel cells, and other electrochemical devices.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Intercalation Cathode Material', 'Rechargeable Battery Cathode', 'Intercalation Anode Material', 'Electrode Intercalation Material', 'Intercalation Compound']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: An Electrochemical Intercalation Material is a material that can reversibly intercalate ions into its structure during electrochemical reactions. These materials are commonly used as cathodes in rechargeable batteries, and can store and release large amounts of energy. Examples include lithium cobalt oxide and lithium iron phosphate.

An electrolyte is a substance that conducts electricity when dissolved in a solvent, typically water. In electrochemical devices, such as batteries and fuel cells, electrolytes are used to transport ions between the electrodes, enabling the flow of electrical current.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Solid-State Electrolyte', 'Non-Liquid Electrolyte', 'Solid Ionic Conductor', 'Solid-State Ion Conductor']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A solid electrolyte is a non-liquid material that can conduct ions. It is used in batteries and fuel cells as an alternative to liquid electrolytes, offering improved safety, stability, and performance. Solid electrolytes can be made from a variety of materials, including ceramics, polymers, and composites.

An Elemental Substance is a pure substance composed of only one type of atom. It cannot be broken down into simpler substances by chemical reactions. Examples include hydrogen, oxygen, carbon, and iron.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Liquid-Liquid Emulsion', 'Oil-in-Water Emulsion', 'Water-in-Oil Emulsion', 'Stable Suspension of Two Immiscible Liquids']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: An emulsion is a type of colloid in which two immiscible liquids are mixed together to form a stable suspension. Emulsions are commonly used in various industrial applications, such as in the production of paints, cosmetics, and food products.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Energy Storage Material', 'Energy Conversion Material', 'Electrochemical Energy Material', 'Energy Device Material', 'Energy Technology Material']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: An Energy Material is a substance or compound that can store, convert, or release energy. It includes materials used in batteries, fuel cells, supercapacitors, and other energy storage and conversion devices.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Er', 'Rare Earth Metal Erbium', 'Erbium Dopant', 'Erbium Neutron Absorber', 'Erbium Colorant']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Erbium is a rare earth metal that is used as a dopant in fiber optic amplifiers and as a neutron absorber in nuclear reactors. It is also used in metallurgy, nuclear technology, and as a colorant in glass and porcelain.

Ethanol is a colorless, flammable liquid that is commonly used as a solvent, fuel, and feedstock in the chemical industry. It is also used as a fuel in fuel cells, where it can be oxidized to produce electricity.

Ethanol is a primary alcohol with the chemical formula C2H5OH. It is a clear, colorless liquid that is commonly used as a solvent, fuel, and disinfectant. In hydrogen technologies, it can be used as a fuel source for fuel cells, and as a hydrogen carrier for storage and transportation.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Eu', 'Rare Earth Metal Europium', 'Europium Dopant', 'Europium Phosphor', 'Europium Neutron Absorber']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Europium is a rare earth metal that is used as a dopant in phosphors for color displays and in nuclear reactors for neutron absorption. It is also used in the production of superconductors and in the manufacture of fluorescent glass.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Carbon Black Conductive Additive F30E', 'High-Purity Conductive Carbon Black F30E', 'F30E Carbon Black', 'Conductive Carbon Black Additive']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: F30E is a high-performance carbon black material used as a conductive additive in lithium-ion batteries. It is characterized by its high purity, low surface area, and high electrical conductivity, making it an ideal material for improving the performance of battery electrodes.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Pt/FC Catalyst', 'Platinum/FCarbon Catalyst', 'Carbon-Supported Pt Catalyst', 'Pt/C Catalyst', 'FC-Pt Catalyst']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: FCarbon Supported Platinum Catalyst is a type of catalyst used in fuel cells, consisting of platinum nanoparticles supported on a carbon substrate. It offers high catalytic activity, stability, and durability, making it suitable for use in proton exchange membrane fuel cells (PEMFCs) and direct methanol fuel cells (DMFCs).

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Pt/C Catalyst F50E', 'Carbon-Supported Pt Catalyst F50E', 'F50E Platinum Catalyst', 'High Surface Area Pt/C Catalyst']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: F50E is a type of carbon-supported platinum catalyst used in fuel cells. It is composed of platinum nanoparticles supported on high surface area carbon black. F50E offers high catalytic activity, durability, and stability under harsh operating conditions.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['High-Temperature F-30E Catalyst', 'F-30E Catalyst for High-Temperature PEMFCs', 'Platinum-Carbon HT Catalyst', 'F-30E-HT Cathode Catalyst', 'Carbon-Supported Platinum HT Catalyst']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: F30E-HT is a high-temperature fuel cell catalyst, consisting of platinum nanoparticles supported on carbon black. It is used as a cathode catalyst in proton exchange membrane fuel cells (PEMFCs) and offers improved durability and performance at elevated temperatures.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['High-Temperature Carbon-Supported Platinum Catalyst', 'F50E Catalyst', 'Platinum Nanoparticle Catalyst', 'HT-PEMFC Catalyst', 'Proton Exchange Membrane Fuel Cell Catalyst']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: F50E-HT is a high-temperature fuel cell catalyst consisting of carbon-supported platinum nanoparticles. It is designed for use in proton exchange membrane fuel cells operating at elevated temperatures, offering improved durability and performance compared to other catalysts.

Fermium is a synthetic, radioactive element with the symbol Fm and atomic number 100. It is a member of the actinide series and is named after physicist Enrico Fermi. Fermium has no known uses outside of basic scientific research.

Flerovium is a synthetic, radioactive element with the symbol Fl and atomic number 114. It is a superheavy element that is produced by bombarding plutonium or curium with calcium ions. Flerovium has no known uses outside of basic scientific research.

A fluid is a substance that has no fixed shape and yields easily to external pressure. It can be a gas or a liquid and is used in various applications in hydrogen technologies, such as in fuel cells and electrolyzers.
State of matter refers to the physical form in which matter exists, such as solid, liquid, or gas. It is an important property of materials that can affect their properties and behavior.

Fluorine is a highly reactive, pale yellow gas that belongs to the halogen group of elements. It is the most electronegative element and is used in various applications such as in the production of uranium, in the manufacture of refrigerants, and in the production of high-temperature plastics.

Foam is a type of material that consists of a gas-filled solid or liquid-filled solid. It is characterized by a high porosity and low density, making it useful in applications such as insulation, cushioning, and filtration.

Francium is a highly radioactive alkali metal with the symbol Fr and atomic number 87. It is the second rarest naturally occurring element in the Earth's crust, and its isotopes are highly unstable, decaying quickly into other elements. Francium has no commercial applications due to its rarity and high radioactivity.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Furnace Carbon Black', 'Thermal Black', 'Channel Black', 'Lamp Black', 'Carbon Black Powder']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Furnace black is a type of carbon black produced by the incomplete combustion of hydrocarbons in a furnace. It is a fine powder with high surface area and is commonly used as a reinforcing filler in rubber and plastic products, as well as a pigment in inks and coatings.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Gd', 'Rare Earth Metal Gd', 'MRI Contrast Agent', 'Neutron Absorber']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Gadolinium is a rare earth metal that is used in hydrogen storage, nuclear reactors, and magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) due to its high magnetic moment and low toxicity. It is also used as a neutron absorber in nuclear power plants.

Gallium is a chemical element with the symbol Ga and atomic number 31. It is a soft, silvery-white metal that is used in various applications such as semiconductors, LEDs, and solar cells. Gallium is also used in the production of alloys and as a liquid metal coolant in nuclear reactors.

A gas is a state of matter that has no fixed shape or volume and expands to fill any available space. Gases are composed of molecules or atoms that are in constant random motion and have weak intermolecular forces.

A Gas-Liquid Suspension is a two-phase mixture consisting of a gas and a liquid, where the gas is dispersed in the liquid phase. It is commonly used in chemical reactions and separations, such as gas-liquid chromatography and gas absorption processes.

A gas solution is a homogeneous mixture of two or more gases. The gases are uniformly distributed and do not settle out upon standing. Gas solutions are commonly used in various applications such as in fuel cells, gas sensors, and gas storage systems.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Gaseous Molecule', 'Gas Phase Molecule', 'Gas State Molecule', 'Gas Phase Compound']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A gas molecule is a group of two or more atoms that are bound together and behave as a single unit in the gaseous state. They are characterized by their low density, high compressibility, and ability to expand to fill any container they are placed in.

A gel is a state of matter that is intermediate between a solid and a liquid. It is a three-dimensional network of solid particles or liquid droplets that are dispersed in a liquid medium. Gels have a unique set of properties, such as high porosity, high surface area, and high mechanical strength, which make them useful in a wide range of applications, including drug delivery, tissue engineering, and food science.

Germanium is a chemical element with the symbol Ge and atomic number 32. It is a lustrous, hard, grayish-white metalloid in the carbon group, chemically similar to its group neighbors tin and silicon. Germanium is used as a semiconductor in transistors and other electronic devices.

Gold is a chemical element with the symbol Au and atomic number 79. It is a highly sought-after precious metal that has been used for coinage, jewelry, and other decorative purposes throughout history. Gold is also used in electronics, aerospace, and medicine due to its excellent conductivity, corrosion resistance, and biocompatibility.
Gore is a brand of expanded polytetrafluoroethylene (ePTFE) material used in various applications, including fuel cells. It is known for its high porosity, chemical resistance, and durability.

Graphite material is a form of carbon that is used in various applications, including as an electrode material in batteries and fuel cells. It has a layered structure that provides good electrical conductivity and mechanical strength.

Hafnium is a chemical element with the symbol Hf and atomic number 72. It is a lustrous, silvery-gray transition metal that is highly resistant to corrosion and wear. Hafnium is used in nuclear reactors, gas turbines, and other high-temperature applications due to its high melting point and ability to absorb neutrons.

Hassium is a synthetic, radioactive element with the symbol Hs and atomic number 108. It is a member of the transactinide series and is highly unstable, with a very short half-life. It has no known biological role and is primarily used for scientific research.

Helium is a chemical element with the symbol He and atomic number 2. It is a colorless, odorless, tasteless, non-toxic, inert, monatomic gas that heads the noble gas series in the periodic table. Its boiling and melting points are the lowest among all the elements.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Heteroatomic Molecule', 'Heteronuclear Compound', 'Heteroatom Molecule', 'Mixed Atom Molecule', 'Mixed Element Molecule']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A heteronuclear molecule is a molecule composed of two or more different elements. It is used in various applications such as catalysis, organic synthesis, and materials science.

A heterogeneous material is a material that consists of two or more physically distinct phases or components. These components can have different chemical compositions, structures, and properties. Examples of heterogeneous materials include composites, alloys, and multiphase ceramics.

Holmium is a rare earth metal that is used as a dopant in fiber optic amplifiers and as a control material in nuclear reactors. It is also used in magnetic data storage and as a component in some electronic devices.

A Homogeneous Material is a material that has uniform composition and properties throughout its volume. It is a material that is made up of the same substance or mixture of substances throughout its entire volume.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Homonuclear Compound', 'Homonuclear Diatomic Molecule', 'Homonuclear Polyatomic Molecule', 'Homonuclear Species']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A Homonuclear Molecule is a molecule composed of two or more atoms of the same element. It is a type of covalent bond where the atoms share electrons to form a stable molecule. Homonuclear molecules are important in materials science as they can form the building blocks of many materials, such as diamond and graphite.

Hydrogen is a chemical element with the symbol H and atomic number 1. It is the lightest and most abundant element in the universe, and is commonly used as a fuel in fuel cells. Hydrogen can be produced from a variety of sources, including natural gas, biomass, and water, and has the potential to be a clean and sustainable energy carrier.

Imidazole is an organic heterocyclic compound with the formula C3H4N2. It is a colorless, crystalline substance that is used as a corrosion inhibitor, a pH indicator, and a building block for the synthesis of pharmaceuticals and other organic compounds.

Indium is a chemical element with the symbol In and atomic number 49. It is a soft, silvery-white metal that is used in the manufacture of semiconductors, alloys, and low-melting-point metal solders. Indium is also used in the production of transparent conductive coatings for touchscreens and solar cells.

Ink is a liquid or paste that contains pigments or dyes and is used to color a surface to produce an image, text, or design. In the context of materials science, ink can refer to a solution or suspension of functional materials, such as catalysts or conductive polymers, that can be deposited onto a substrate using printing techniques.

Ink is a liquid or paste that contains pigments or dyes and is used to color a surface to produce an image, text, or design. In the context of materials science, ink can refer to a solution or suspension of functional materials, such as catalysts or semiconductors, that can be deposited onto a substrate using printing techniques.

An inorganic compound is a chemical compound that does not contain carbon-hydrogen bonds. They are typically derived from non-living sources, such as minerals, and can have a wide range of applications in materials science, including as catalysts, semiconductors, and pigments.

An organic compound is a type of chemical compound that contains carbon atoms bonded to hydrogen atoms, along with other elements such as oxygen, nitrogen, sulfur, and halogens. Organic compounds are widely used in hydrogen technologies, including as solvents, electrolytes, and catalysts.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Intercalation Compound', 'Intercalation Host Material', 'Intercalation Electrode Material', 'Intercalation Cathode Material']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Intercalation materials are materials that can reversibly incorporate ions or molecules between their layers or within their structures. They are used in batteries, supercapacitors, and other electrochemical devices as electrode materials, offering high energy density and long cycle life.

Iodine is a non-metallic element that is commonly used in redox flow batteries as an active material in the electrolyte. It is also used in dye-sensitized solar cells and as a dopant in semiconductors.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['IL Electrolyte', 'Ionic Liquid-Based Electrolyte', 'Room-Temperature Ionic Liquid Electrolyte', 'RTIL Electrolyte']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: An Ionic Liquid Electrolyte is a type of electrolyte composed entirely of ionic liquids, which are salts that are liquid at or near room temperature. They are used in electrochemical devices such as batteries and fuel cells, offering high ionic conductivity, low volatility, and wide electrochemical stability windows.

Iridium is a rare, hard, and brittle transition metal with a high melting point. It is used as a catalyst in various chemical reactions, including in the production of fertilizers, pharmaceuticals, and plastics. It is also used in the electronics industry for its resistance to corrosion and high-temperature stability.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['IrOx Catalyst', 'Iridium-Based Catalyst', 'Iridium Oxide Electrode', 'IrO2 Catalyst', 'Iridium Oxide Coated Electrode']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Iridium oxide catalyst is a type of heterogeneous catalyst that is used in various electrochemical applications, such as fuel cells, water electrolysis, and sensors. It is known for its high catalytic activity, stability, and resistance to corrosion.

Iron is a chemical element with the symbol Fe and atomic number 26. It is a metal that is commonly used in the production of steel and other alloys. Iron is also used in the production of magnets, catalysts, and pigments.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Isotropic Substance', 'Isotropic Solid', 'Isotropic Material Property', 'Isotropic Physical Property']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: An isotropic material is a material that has the same physical properties in all directions. It has no preferred direction of orientation and exhibits the same mechanical, thermal, and electrical properties in all directions. Examples of isotropic materials include glass, metals, and some plastics.

Krypton is a noble gas element with the symbol Kr and atomic number 36. It is a colorless, odorless, tasteless gas that is used in some types of gas discharge lamps, photographic flash lamps, and as a filling gas for energy-efficient windows.

Lamp black is a type of carbon black that is produced by the incomplete combustion of oils or gases. It is a fine black powder that is used as a pigment in inks, paints, and plastics, as well as a filler in rubber products.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['La', 'Rare Earth Metal Lanthanum', 'Lanthanide', 'Nickel-Metal Hydride Battery Material']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Lanthanum is a rare earth element with the atomic number 57. It is a silvery-white metal that is ductile, malleable, and soft enough to be cut with a knife. Lanthanum is used in the production of nickel-metal hydride batteries, camera lenses, and carbon arc lamps.

Lawrencium is a synthetic, radioactive chemical element with the symbol Lr and atomic number 103. It is a member of the actinide series of elements and is named after physicist Ernest Lawrence. Lawrencium has no known biological role and is primarily used for scientific research purposes.

Lead is a heavy metal element with the symbol Pb. It is commonly used in batteries, radiation shielding, and as a component in solder and alloys. However, it is toxic and poses a risk to human health and the environment.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Ammonium-Zinc Chloride Electrolyte', 'Dry Cell Electrolyte', 'Leclanché Battery Electrolyte', 'NH4Cl-ZnCl2 Electrolyte']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Leclanché electrolyte is a type of electrolyte used in primary batteries, consisting of a mixture of ammonium chloride and zinc chloride. It is commonly used in dry cell batteries, offering good electrical conductivity and stability.

A Near-Neutral Electrolyte is an electrolyte solution with a pH close to 7. It is used in electrochemical applications such as batteries and fuel cells, where a neutral pH is desired to minimize corrosion and improve stability.

A liquid is a state of matter that has a definite volume but no fixed shape. It can flow and take the shape of its container. Liquids are commonly used as solvents, electrolytes, and reactants in chemical reactions.
A liquid aerosol is a suspension of liquid droplets in a gas. It is commonly used in spray applications, such as in fuel injectors, humidifiers, and medical inhalers.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Solid Particle Aerosol', 'Dust Aerosol', 'Particulate Matter Aerosol', 'Solid Dispersion Aerosol']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A solid aerosol is a suspension of solid particles in a gas, typically air. These particles can be of various sizes and shapes, and can be composed of different materials. Solid aerosols can be generated naturally or artificially, and can have various effects on human health and the environment.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Foam Dispersion', 'Liquid Bubble Dispersion', 'Liquid Foam Colloid', 'Foam Emulsion']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A liquid foam is a dispersion of gas bubbles in a liquid, where the bubbles are separated by thin liquid films. It is a type of colloid and can be formed by mechanical or chemical means. Liquid foams have applications in various fields, including food, cosmetics, and fire extinguishers.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Solid Cellular Material', 'Solid Foam Material', 'Porous Solid Material', 'Solid Sponge Material']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A solid foam is a type of foam that consists of a solid material with a large number of small pores or bubbles throughout its structure. It is used in various applications such as insulation, cushioning, and soundproofing due to its lightweight, high strength, and thermal insulation properties.
A Liquid-Gas Suspension is a heterogeneous mixture of a liquid and a gas, where the gas is dispersed throughout the liquid phase. Examples include foam and emulsions.

A Liquid-Liquid Suspension is a heterogeneous mixture of two immiscible liquids, where one liquid is dispersed in the other liquid in the form of small droplets. The droplets are stabilized by surfactants or emulsifiers, and the suspension can be used in various applications such as in the food industry, pharmaceuticals, and cosmetics.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Molecule in Liquid State', 'Liquid Phase Molecule', 'Molecule in Liquid Form']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A liquid molecule is a molecule that exists in a liquid state of matter at standard temperature and pressure. It has a definite volume but no fixed shape, and can flow and take the shape of its container. Examples of liquid molecules include water, ethanol, and benzene.

A liquid sol is a homogeneous mixture of two or more substances, where one of the substances is a liquid and the other is typically a solid, liquid, or gas. The liquid component is the solvent, and the other component(s) is/are the solute(s). Liquid sols are commonly used in chemical synthesis, catalysis, and electrochemistry.

A Liquid-Solid Suspension is a heterogeneous mixture consisting of a liquid phase and solid particles that are suspended in the liquid. The solid particles are insoluble in the liquid and can settle over time. These suspensions are used in various applications, such as in the chemical industry, pharmaceuticals, and food industry.

A phase homogeneous mixture is a type of mixture where the components are uniformly distributed throughout the mixture, resulting in a single phase. The composition of the mixture is the same throughout and the properties of the mixture are uniform. Examples of phase homogeneous mixtures include solutions and alloys.

Lithium is a chemical element with the symbol Li and atomic number 3. It is a soft, silvery-white alkali metal that is highly reactive and flammable. Lithium is commonly used in rechargeable batteries, ceramics, glass, and as a medication to treat bipolar disorder.

Livermorium is a synthetic, radioactive element with the symbol Lv and atomic number 116. It is a member of the group 16 elements and is expected to have similar properties to its lighter homologues, such as oxygen, sulfur, and selenium. Livermorium has no known biological role and is primarily used for scientific research.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Lu', 'Rare Earth Metal Lu', 'Heavy Rare Earth Metal', 'Lutetium Element']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Lutetium is a rare earth metal with the atomic number 71. It is a silvery-white metal and is the heaviest and hardest of the rare earth elements. It is used in the production of catalysts, superconductors, and nuclear reactor technology.

A macromolecule is a large molecule composed of repeating subunits, such as proteins, nucleic acids, and synthetic polymers. They are important in materials science as they can exhibit unique properties due to their size and structure.

A Polyatomic Entity is a molecule composed of two or more atoms held together by covalent bonds. It can be organic or inorganic and can have a variety of shapes and sizes. Polyatomic entities are important in many chemical reactions and play a crucial role in the formation of materials.

Magnesium is a chemical element with the symbol Mg and atomic number 12. It is a lightweight, silvery-white metal that is commonly used in alloys with other metals to improve their mechanical properties. Magnesium is also used in the production of batteries, particularly in the form of magnesium-ion batteries.

Manganese is a chemical element with the symbol Mn and atomic number 25. It is a transition metal and is commonly used as a cathode material in lithium-ion batteries due to its high specific capacity and low cost. Manganese is also used in the production of steel and other alloys.

A manufactured material is a material that is produced through human intervention, typically involving chemical or physical processing. Examples include engineered nanoparticles, thin films, and composite materials.

Meitnerium is a synthetic, radioactive element with the symbol Mt and atomic number 109. It is a highly unstable element that has only been produced in small amounts and for research purposes. Its properties are not well known, but it is believed to be a solid metal at room temperature.

Mendelevium is a synthetic, radioactive, metallic element with the atomic number 101. It is a member of the actinide series and is named after the Russian chemist Dmitri Mendeleev, who is credited with the development of the periodic table. Mendelevium has no known uses outside of basic scientific research.

Mercury is a chemical element with the symbol Hg and atomic number 80. It is a heavy, silvery-white metal that is liquid at room temperature. Mercury is commonly used in thermometers, barometers, and other scientific instruments, as well as in dental fillings and some electrical switches. It is also used in the production of chlorine and caustic soda.

A metal is a solid material that is typically hard, shiny, malleable, ductile, and a good conductor of heat and electricity. Metals are widely used in various applications, including construction, transportation, electronics, and energy production.

Methanol is a colorless, flammable liquid that is used as a solvent, fuel, and antifreeze. It is also used in the production of formaldehyde and other chemicals. Methanol is a toxic substance and can cause blindness or death if ingested or inhaled.

Molybdenum is a refractory metal that is commonly used in high-temperature applications such as furnace linings, missile parts, and aircraft parts. It is also used as an alloying element in steel and other metals to improve their strength and corrosion resistance.

Moscovium is a synthetic, radioactive element with the symbol Mc and atomic number 115. It is a member of the group 15 elements and is currently only produced in nuclear reactors. Its properties are not well known due to its short half-life and difficulty in producing it in large quantities.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Perfluorinated Sulfonic Acid Polymer', 'Nafion Membrane', 'Nafion Polymer', 'PFSA Polymer', 'Sulfonated Tetrafluoroethylene Copolymer']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Nafion is a perfluorinated sulfonic acid polymer used as a membrane material in fuel cells and other electrochemical devices. It has high proton conductivity, chemical stability, and mechanical strength, making it an ideal material for use in harsh environments.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['D2020CS', 'Nafion Membrane', 'Perfluorinated Sulfonic Acid Membrane', 'Nafion D2020', 'Nafion Proton Exchange Membrane']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Nafion D2020CS is a perfluorinated sulfonic acid ionomer membrane used in fuel cells and other electrochemical devices. It has high proton conductivity, good chemical stability, and excellent mechanical properties. It is commonly used as a proton exchange membrane in fuel cells.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['D2021CS', 'Nafion Membrane', 'Perfluorinated Sulfonic Acid Membrane', 'Proton Exchange Membrane', 'PEM']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Nafion D2021CS is a perfluorinated sulfonic acid ionomer membrane used in fuel cells and other electrochemical devices. It is a highly conductive, chemically stable, and mechanically durable membrane that can operate at high temperatures and low relative humidity. It is commonly used as a proton exchange membrane in fuel cells.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Perfluorinated Sulfonic Acid Polymer', 'Nafion Membrane', 'Proton Exchange Membrane', 'PEM', 'Nafion_D2020CS Membrane', 'Nafion_D2021CS Membrane', 'Nafion_D520CS Membrane']

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Perfluorinated Sulfonic Acid Polymer', 'Nafion Membrane', 'Nafion_D2020CS Membrane', 'Nafion_D2021CS Membrane', 'Nafion_D520CS Membrane', 'Nafion_D521CS Membrane']
