Nafion_D2020CS, Nafion_D2021CS, Nafion_D520CS, and Nafion_D521CS are different types of Nafion membranes with varying thickness and properties.

A nanomaterial is a material with at least one dimension in the nanometer range (1-100 nm). These materials have unique properties due to their small size, such as high surface area, quantum confinement, and enhanced reactivity. They have applications in various fields, including electronics, energy, and medicine.

A natural material is a substance that occurs naturally in the environment, without any human intervention. Examples of natural materials include wood, stone, and minerals. These materials are often used in various applications, such as construction, furniture, and jewelry.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Nd', 'Rare Earth Element Nd', 'Neodymium Metal', 'Nd Magnet Material']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Neodymium is a rare earth element that is used in the production of high-strength magnets, such as those used in electric motors and generators. It is also used in the production of glass, ceramics, and steel alloys.
Neon is a chemical element with the symbol Ne and atomic number 10. It is a noble gas that is colorless, odorless, and inert. Neon is used in lighting, advertising, and cryogenics.

Neptunium is a radioactive, silvery-white, actinide metal that is commonly used as a precursor in nuclear reactors. It is also used in the production of plutonium and as a component in neutron detection equipment.

Nickel is a metallic element with the symbol Ni and atomic number 28. It is a silvery-white lustrous metal with a slight golden tinge. Nickel is used in various applications, including the production of stainless steel, batteries, and catalysts.

Nihonium is a synthetic, highly radioactive element with the symbol Nh and atomic number 113. It is a member of the group 13 elements and is expected to have properties similar to those of boron, aluminum, and gallium. Nihonium has no known biological role and is primarily used for scientific research purposes.

Niobium is a chemical element with the symbol Nb and atomic number 41. It is a soft, grey, ductile transition metal, often used in alloys with other metals to improve their strength and corrosion resistance. Niobium is also used in superconducting materials, electronic components, and in the aerospace industry.

Nitrogen is a chemical element with the symbol N and atomic number 7. It is a colorless, odorless, and tasteless gas that makes up 78% of the Earth's atmosphere. Nitrogen is an important component in many industrial processes, including the production of ammonia for fertilizers and the production of electronics.

Nobelium is a synthetic, radioactive element with the symbol No and atomic number 102. It is a member of the actinide series and is named after Alfred Nobel, the inventor of dynamite. Nobelium has no known uses outside of basic scientific research.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Organic Electrolyte', 'Non-Water-Based Electrolyte', 'Non-Aqueous Solution', 'Non-Aqueous Battery Electrolyte', 'Non-Aqueous Fuel Cell Electrolyte']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A Non-Aqueous Electrolyte is an electrolyte solution that does not contain water as a solvent. It is commonly used in batteries and fuel cells, offering improved stability, wider operating temperature range, and higher energy density compared to aqueous electrolytes.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Nonpolar Solvent', 'Nonpolar Liquid', 'Nonpolar Organic Solvent', 'Nonpolar Reaction Medium']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A non-polar solvent is a liquid substance that does not have a dipole moment and does not dissolve in water. It is used in various applications such as extraction, cleaning, and as a reaction medium in organic synthesis.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Dipolar Solvent', 'Polar Liquid', 'Polar Covalent Solvent', 'Polar Molecule Solvent']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A polar solvent is a liquid substance that has a dipole moment, meaning it has a separation of electric charge. Polar solvents dissolve polar solutes and are commonly used in chemical reactions and extractions.

Oganesson is a synthetic, highly radioactive element with the symbol Og and atomic number 118. It is a member of the noble gases group and is currently the heaviest element known. Due to its high radioactivity and short half-life, it has no practical applications outside of basic scientific research.

Osmium is a hard, brittle, blue-gray or blue-black transition metal in the platinum group. It is used in alloys with other metals, electrical contacts, and fountain pen nibs. It is also used as a catalyst in chemical reactions and in the production of synthetic fibers.

An oxidant is a chemical substance that can accept electrons from another substance, causing it to undergo oxidation. It is commonly used in batteries and fuel cells to facilitate the electrochemical reactions that generate electrical energy.

Oxygen is a chemical element with the symbol O and atomic number 8. It is a member of the chalcogen group on the periodic table, a highly reactive nonmetal, and an oxidizing agent that readily forms oxides with most elements as well as with other compounds.

Palladium is a chemical element with the symbol Pd and atomic number 46. It is a rare and lustrous silvery-white metal that is used in various applications, including catalysis, electronics, and jewelry. Palladium is also used as a catalyst in fuel cells, where it helps to facilitate the electrochemical reactions that convert chemical energy into electrical energy.

Phase of matter refers to the physical state of a substance, such as solid, liquid, or gas. It is determined by the arrangement of particles and the strength of the forces between them. Other phases of matter include plasma and Bose-Einstein condensates.

Phosphorus is a chemical element with the symbol P and atomic number 15. It is a non-metal that can exist in several allotropic forms, including white, red, and black phosphorus. It is used in the production of fertilizers, pesticides, and other chemicals, as well as in the semiconductor industry.

Plasma is a state of matter consisting of a gas-like mixture of positively charged ions, negatively charged electrons, and neutral particles. It is formed when a gas is heated to high temperatures or subjected to strong electromagnetic fields, causing the atoms to ionize and become highly reactive. Plasma has many applications in materials science, including plasma processing, surface modification, and plasma-assisted deposition.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Pt', 'Platinum Metal', 'Platinum Catalyst', 'Platinum Group Metal', 'Highly Reactive Catalyst']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Platinum is a chemical element with the symbol Pt and atomic number 78. It is a dense, malleable, and ductile metal that is resistant to corrosion and tarnishing. Platinum is widely used as a catalyst in chemical reactions, including in fuel cells, due to its high catalytic activity and stability.
Plutonium is a radioactive, silvery-white metal that is used as a fuel in nuclear reactors and in nuclear weapons. It is highly toxic and poses a significant health hazard if ingested or inhaled.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Po', 'Radioactive Metal', 'Uranium Ore Metal', 'Thermoelectric Heat Source', 'Nuclear Battery Material']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Polonium is a rare, radioactive, and highly toxic metal that occurs naturally in uranium ores. It has limited applications in industry, including as a heat source in thermoelectric power generators and in nuclear batteries.

Polyepoxide is a polymer made by the reaction of an epoxide with a curing agent. It is commonly used as a coating material due to its excellent adhesion, chemical resistance, and mechanical properties. Polyepoxides are also used in the production of composites, adhesives, and electrical insulation materials.

Potassium is a chemical element with the symbol K and atomic number 19. It is a soft, silvery-white metal that reacts violently with water and air. Potassium is an important element for biological systems and is found in many minerals, including feldspar and mica.

Praseodymium is a rare earth metal that is used as an alloying agent in the production of permanent magnets, as well as in the manufacture of carbon arc lights and other electronic components. It is also used in the production of glass and ceramics.
Promethium is a rare earth metal that is radioactive and has no stable isotopes. It is used in nuclear batteries, luminous paint, and atomic clocks.

Protactinium is a rare and highly radioactive element with the atomic number 91. It is a silvery-gray metal that readily reacts with oxygen, water vapor, and acids. Protactinium is used in research and nuclear reactors, and its isotopes have potential applications in nuclear weapons.

Radium is a highly radioactive, rare earth metal that is silvery-white in color. It is used in luminous paints, as a source of alpha, beta, and gamma rays for medical purposes, and in nuclear physics research.

Radon is a radioactive, colorless, and odorless gas that is formed by the decay of radium. It is a naturally occurring element and is found in soil, rock, and water. Radon is a health hazard and can cause lung cancer when inhaled over prolonged periods.

A reactive material is a substance that can undergo a chemical reaction, often exothermic, with other substances in its environment. These materials are often used in energy storage and conversion applications, such as batteries and fuel cells.

A reductant is a substance that donates electrons to another substance in a chemical reaction. It is used to reduce the oxidation state of the other substance. In hydrogen technologies, reductants are used in fuel cells to facilitate the electrochemical reaction that converts chemical energy into electrical energy.

Rhenium is a rare, silvery-white, heavy metal with a high melting point and excellent wear resistance. It is used as an alloying element in superalloys for jet engine parts, in electrical contacts, and in catalysts for the petroleum industry.

Rhodium is a rare, silvery-white metal that is corrosion-resistant and has a high melting point. It is used as a catalyst in various chemical reactions, including in the production of nitric acid and in catalytic converters for automobiles.

Roentgenium is a synthetic, highly radioactive element with the symbol Rg and atomic number 111. It is a member of the group 11 elements and is predicted to have properties similar to those of silver, gold, and copper. Roentgenium has no known biological role and is primarily used for scientific research purposes.

Rubidium is a soft, silvery-white metallic element belonging to the alkali metal group. It is highly reactive and can ignite spontaneously in air. Rubidium is used in atomic clocks, photoelectric cells, and as a getter in vacuum tubes.

Ruthenium is a transition metal element with the symbol Ru and atomic number 44. It is a hard, silvery-white metal that is used as a catalyst in various chemical reactions, including in the production of fertilizers, petrochemicals, and pharmaceuticals. Ruthenium is also used in the electronics industry and in the manufacture of alloys for use in electrical contacts and jewelry.

Rutherfordium is a synthetic, radioactive element with the symbol Rf and atomic number 104. It is a member of the transactinide series of elements and is named after physicist Ernest Rutherford. Rutherfordium is produced by bombarding lighter elements with heavy ions in a particle accelerator.

A salt molecule is a chemical compound composed of cations and anions held together by ionic bonds. They are typically solids at room temperature and are often soluble in water. Salts are commonly used in various industrial processes, such as in the production of fertilizers, dyes, and pharmaceuticals.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Sm', 'Rare Earth Metal Sm', 'Samarium-Cobalt Magnet Material', 'Samarium Oxide', 'Samarium Metal']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Samarium is a rare earth metal that is used in the production of permanent magnets, as well as in nuclear reactors and X-ray tubes. It is also used in the production of samarium-cobalt magnets, which are used in electric motors and other applications that require strong magnetic fields.

A saturated solution is a solution in which the maximum amount of solute has been dissolved in a solvent at a given temperature and pressure. Any additional solute added will not dissolve and will remain as a solid at the bottom of the container. Saturated solutions are commonly used in chemical reactions and separations.

Scandium is a rare earth metal that is used as an alloying element in various applications, including aerospace, defense, and electronics. It is also used in solid oxide fuel cells and as a catalyst in organic reactions.

Seaborgium is a synthetic, radioactive chemical element with the symbol Sg and atomic number 106. It is a highly unstable element that has only been produced in small amounts and for very short periods of time. It is primarily used for scientific research purposes.

A secondary catalyst is a material that is used in conjunction with a primary catalyst to enhance its performance. It can modify the surface properties of the primary catalyst, increase its stability, or improve its selectivity. Secondary catalysts are often used in heterogeneous catalysis, where they can be added as a coating or a promoter to the primary catalyst.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Se', 'Non-metallic element', 'Photovoltaic cell material', 'Glass manufacturing material', 'Photoconductive material']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Selenium is a non-metallic element that is used in the production of photovoltaic cells, glass manufacturing, and pigments. It is also used in the electronics industry as a component of photoconductive and photovoltaic devices.

Silicon is a chemical element with the symbol Si and atomic number 14. It is a hard, brittle crystalline solid with a blue-grey metallic lustre, and is a tetravalent metalloid and semiconductor. It is widely used in the electronics industry for making microchips and solar cells.

Silver is a chemical element with the symbol Ag and atomic number 47. It is a soft, white, lustrous transition metal that exhibits the highest electrical conductivity, thermal conductivity, and reflectivity of any metal. Silver is used in various applications, including electrical contacts, jewelry, and silverware.

Smoke is a collection of airborne solid and liquid particulates and gases emitted when a material undergoes combustion. It is a complex mixture of organic and inorganic compounds, including carbon monoxide, nitrogen oxides, and polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (PAHs).

Sodium is a highly reactive alkali metal that is commonly used as a reducing agent in chemical reactions. It is also used in the production of various chemicals, such as sodium hydroxide and sodium carbonate. Sodium is an important element in the human body, playing a key role in regulating fluid balance and nerve function.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Solid-Air Suspension', 'Dust Cloud', 'Aerosol', 'Particulate Matter in Air', 'Solid-Atmosphere Mixture']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A Solid-Gas Suspension is a heterogeneous mixture consisting of solid particles suspended in a gas. It is commonly formed by the dispersion of solid particles in air, and can be created by various processes such as grinding, crushing, or milling. Solid-gas suspensions are used in various applications such as air pollution control, powder processing, and combustion.

A Solid-Liquid Suspension is a heterogeneous mixture consisting of solid particles dispersed in a liquid medium. The solid particles are usually insoluble in the liquid and can settle over time due to gravity. These suspensions are commonly used in various industrial applications, such as in the production of ceramics, pharmaceuticals, and paints.

A Solid-Liquid Suspension is a heterogeneous mixture consisting of solid particles dispersed in a liquid medium. The solid particles are usually insoluble in the liquid and can settle over time. Solid-liquid suspensions are commonly used in various industrial processes, such as wastewater treatment, mineral processing, and pharmaceuticals.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Solid-State Solution', 'Homogeneous Solid Mixture', 'Solid-Solid Solution', 'Alloy', 'Solid Solution Alloy']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A solid solution is a solid-state mixture of two or more substances, where one substance is dissolved in the other. The resulting material has a uniform composition and properties throughout the bulk of the material. Solid solutions are commonly used in materials science to tailor the properties of materials, such as strength, hardness, and conductivity.

A Solid-Solid Suspension is a heterogeneous mixture of two or more solid materials, where one material is dispersed throughout the other in the form of small particles. The particles are usually insoluble in the solvent and can settle over time. Solid-solid suspensions are used in various applications, including drug delivery, cosmetics, and food industry.
A solute is a substance that is dissolved in a solvent to form a solution. In electrochemistry, solutes are often ions that carry an electric charge and participate in electrochemical reactions.
A solute is a substance that is dissolved in a solvent to form a solution. In electrochemistry, solutes are often ions that carry an electric charge and participate in electrochemical reactions.

A solvent molecule is a molecule that dissolves another substance, called a solute, to form a homogeneous mixture called a solution. Solvent molecules have a polar or nonpolar structure, depending on the solute they are dissolving. They are commonly used in chemical reactions and separations in various industries, including pharmaceuticals, food, and chemical manufacturing.
Spray is a dispersion of liquid droplets in a gas. It is commonly used in fuel injection systems, coating applications, and medical treatments.

A strong acid is a chemical compound that completely dissociates into its ions in water, producing a high concentration of hydrogen ions (H+). Strong acids have a pH less than 3 and are commonly used in industrial processes, such as metal cleaning and etching.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Weakly Acidic Compound', 'Low Dissociation Acid', 'Acid with Low Dissociation Constant']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A weak acid is an acid that partially dissociates into ions in an aqueous solution. It has a low dissociation constant and a low concentration of hydrogen ions. Weak acids are commonly used in chemical reactions and as buffers in various applications.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Highly Basic Compound', 'Strongly Alkaline Substance', 'Strongly Basic Substance']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A strong base is a chemical compound that can completely dissociate in water to produce hydroxide ions (OH-) and cations. It has a high pH value and can neutralize strong acids. Strong bases are commonly used in various chemical reactions, such as in the production of soaps and detergents, and in the treatment of wastewater.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Weakly Basic Compound', 'Weakly Basic Substance', 'Weakly Basic Molecule']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A weak base is a chemical compound that can accept a proton (H+) but does not completely dissociate in water. It has a lower affinity for protons than a strong base and has a higher pH value. Weak bases are commonly used in acid-base titrations and in the production of pharmaceuticals and fertilizers.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Sr', 'Alkaline Earth Metal', 'Strontium Metal', 'Strontium Getter', 'Strontium Ferrite Magnet']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Strontium is a chemical element with the symbol Sr and atomic number 38. It is a soft, silvery-white metal that belongs to the group of alkaline earth metals. Strontium has several applications in hydrogen technologies, including as a getter in vacuum tubes, in the production of ferrite magnets, and as a dopant in solid oxide fuel cells.

Sulfur is a non-metallic chemical element with the symbol S and atomic number 16. It is an abundant, multivalent non-metal, and an essential element for life. Sulfur is used in various applications, including the production of sulfuric acid, fertilizers, and rubber products.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Additive Electrolyte', 'Conductive Salt', 'Performance Enhancing Electrolyte', 'Stabilizing Electrolyte', 'Auxiliary Electrolyte']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A Supporting Electrolyte is an electrolyte that is added to an electrochemical cell to improve its performance. It is typically a salt that is added to the electrolyte solution to increase its conductivity and stability. Supporting electrolytes are commonly used in electrochemical applications such as batteries, fuel cells, and sensors.

Supporting electrolyte is an electrolyte that is added to an electrochemical cell to improve its performance. It is used to increase the conductivity of the electrolyte and to stabilize the electrode potential. Supporting electrolytes are often used in electrochemical experiments and in the production of electrochemical devices such as batteries and fuel cells.
Technetium is a radioactive, silvery-gray metal that is commonly used as a tracer in medical imaging. It is also used in nuclear medicine and in the production of nuclear weapons.

Tellurium is a chemical element with the symbol Te and atomic number 52. It is a brittle, mildly toxic, rare, silver-white metalloid. Tellurium is used in the production of cadmium telluride solar panels, thermoelectric devices, and rewritable optical discs. It is also used as an alloying agent in steel and copper to improve machinability.

Tennessine is a synthetic element with the symbol Ts and atomic number 117. It is a highly radioactive metal that has only been produced in minute amounts and has not been studied extensively. Its properties are not well known, but it is expected to be a solid at room temperature and have similar chemical properties to other elements in the same group of the periodic table.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Tb', 'Rare Earth Metal Terbium', 'Terbium Dopant', 'Terbium Neutron Absorber']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Terbium is a rare earth metal that is used as a dopant in solid-state devices, such as solid-state lighting and lasers. It is also used in nuclear reactors as a neutron absorber and in alloys for magnetostrictive materials.

A Ternary Catalyst is a type of catalyst composed of three different elements, often used in electrochemical reactions. It offers improved catalytic activity, selectivity, and stability compared to binary catalysts.

A Ternary Material is a material composed of three different elements or compounds. In the context of hydrogen technologies, ternary materials are often used as catalysts or electrode materials in fuel cells and electrolyzers.

Thallium is a chemical element with the symbol Tl and atomic number 81. It is a soft, gray post-transition metal that is not found free in nature. Thallium is used in the electronics industry, in the manufacture of optical lenses, and as a medical radioisotope.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Thermal Carbon Black', 'Conductive Carbon Black', 'Thermal Black Carbon', 'Incomplete Combustion Carbon Black']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Thermal black is a type of carbon black produced by the incomplete combustion of hydrocarbons. It is used as a conductive filler in various applications, including batteries, fuel cells, and supercapacitors.

Thorium is a radioactive, silvery-white metal that is commonly used as a nuclear fuel in nuclear reactors. It is also used in magnesium alloys, electronic equipment, and as a catalyst in organic chemical reactions.

Thulium is a rare earth metal that is used in high-temperature superconductors, portable X-ray machines, and lasers. It is also used as a dopant in fiber optic amplifiers and as a radiation source in portable X-ray fluorescence (XRF) analyzers.

Tin is a chemical element with the symbol Sn and atomic number 50. It is a silvery-white, soft, malleable, and ductile metal that is widely used in various applications such as soldering, coating, and plating. Tin is also used in the manufacturing of various alloys, including bronze, pewter, and solder.

Titanium is a metallic element with the symbol Ti and atomic number 22. It is a strong, lightweight, and corrosion-resistant material that is widely used in aerospace, medical implants, and other industrial applications.

Tungsten is a chemical element with the symbol W and atomic number 74. It is a hard, dense, steel-gray metal that is commonly used in electrical contacts, filaments, and high-temperature applications due to its high melting point and excellent thermal and electrical conductivity.

Ununennium is a synthetic, highly radioactive element with the symbol Uue and atomic number 119. It is also known as eka-francium or element 119. It has not been produced in sufficient quantities to determine its properties, but it is predicted to be a metal and part of the alkali metal group.

Uranium is a radioactive, metallic element that is commonly used as a fuel in nuclear reactors. It is also used in the production of nuclear weapons and has various other industrial applications. Uranium is a heavy metal that is toxic and poses a significant health risk if ingested or inhaled.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['V', 'Transition Metal V', 'Vanadium Redox Flow Battery', 'Vanadium Alloy']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Vanadium is a chemical element with the symbol V and atomic number 23. It is a hard, silvery-grey, ductile, and malleable transition metal. Vanadium is used as a strengthening agent in steel and titanium alloys, and in the production of vanadium redox batteries.

Vapor is a gaseous state of a substance that is normally in a solid or liquid state at room temperature and pressure. It is formed when a substance evaporates or sublimates and can be condensed back into a liquid or solid state by cooling or increasing pressure.

Water is a transparent, tasteless, odorless, and nearly colorless chemical substance that is the main constituent of Earth's streams, lakes, and oceans, and the fluids of most living organisms. It is vital for all known forms of life, even though it provides no calories or organic nutrients.

Ytterbium is a rare earth element with the symbol Yb and atomic number 70. It is a soft, malleable, and ductile metal that is often used as a doping agent in stainless steel and other alloys. Ytterbium has potential applications in atomic clocks, lasers, and nuclear medicine.

owl:Class.alternative_labels: ['Y', 'Rare Earth Metal Yttrium', 'Yttrium Dopant', 'Yttrium Oxide', 'Yttrium Superconductor']
owl:Class.rdfs:comment: Yttrium is a rare earth metal that is used as a dopant in materials science, particularly in the production of solid-state lasers and superconductors. It is also used in the production of electrodes, electrolytes, and phosphors.

Zinc is a chemical element with the symbol Zn and atomic number 30. It is a bluish-white, lustrous, and relatively soft metal that is widely used in various applications, including galvanizing, alloys, and batteries. Zinc is also an essential nutrient for humans and animals.

Zirconium is a chemical element with the symbol Zr and atomic number 40. It is a lustrous, grey-white, strong transition metal that resembles titanium. Zirconium is used in nuclear reactors due to its low neutron-capture cross-section and resistance to corrosion.

0D NanoMaterials are nanoscale materials with zero-dimensional structures, such as quantum dots, fullerenes, and nanospheres. They have unique electronic, optical, and magnetic properties, making them useful in various applications, including electronics, energy, and biomedicine.
